T1  - Functional Background as A Determinant of Executives' Selective Perception
AU  - Waller, Mary J.
AU  - Huber, George P.
AU  - Glick, William H.
Y1  - 1995/08/01
PY  - 1995
DA  - 1995/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256616
DO  - 10.5465/256616
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 943
EP  - 974
VL  - 38
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - What executives perceive influences their actions. These actions in turn affect the nature and performance of their organizations. Thus, what executives perceive is of interest to organizational scientists, to strategic management researchers, and to organizational stakeholders. The results of the field study reported here indicate that, contrary to popular belief, functional area work experience has no effect on which changes lop executives perceive in their organizations' environments. Functional background, however, does have an effect on which changes they perceive in their organizations' effectiveness.
AB  - What executives perceive influences their actions. These actions in turn affect the nature and performance of their organizations. Thus, what executives perceive is of interest to organizational scientists, to strategic management researchers, and to organizational stakeholders. The results of the field study reported here indicate that, contrary to popular belief, functional area work experience has no effect on which changes lop executives perceive in their organizations' environments. Functional background, however, does have an effect on which changes they perceive in their organizations' effectiveness.
