TY  - JOUR
T1  - Espoused Values and Organizational Change Themes
AU  - Kabanoff, Boris
AU  - Waldersee, Robert
AU  - Cohen, Marcus
Y1  - 1995/08/01
PY  - 1995
DA  - 1995/08/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256621
DO  - 10.5465/256621
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 1075
EP  - 1104
VL  - 38
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - Using computer-aided content analysis, we assessed the strength of nine values?authority, performance, reward, normative, commitment, participation, leadership, teamwork, and affiliation?in 88 large Australian organizations. Cluster analysis was used to categorize each organization as having one of four value structures: elite, leadership, meritocratic, or collegial. Organizations classified as having different value structures differed in a theoretically consistent way in how their members described organizational change. We discuss the implications of these findings for the values theory and the use of content analysis for the study of organizational values.
AB  - Using computer-aided content analysis, we assessed the strength of nine values?authority, performance, reward, normative, commitment, participation, leadership, teamwork, and affiliation?in 88 large Australian organizations. Cluster analysis was used to categorize each organization as having one of four value structures: elite, leadership, meritocratic, or collegial. Organizations classified as having different value structures differed in a theoretically consistent way in how their members described organizational change. We discuss the implications of these findings for the values theory and the use of content analysis for the study of organizational values.
SN  - 0001-4273
M3  - doi: 10.5465/256621
UR  - https://doi.org/10.5465/256621
Y2  - 2026/04/24
